azette.com |date=22 January 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/entertainment/wanna-be-comedy-infamous-article-1.476285 |title=Wanna-Be Comedy: Almost Infamous|newspaper=[[New York Daily News]]|date=14 March 2002}}</ref>\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[Gilmore Girls]]''\n|Claude Clemenceau\n|Episode: \"A Deep-Fried Korean Thanksgiving\" (S 3:Ep 9)\n|<ref name=\"TV,com\" />\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[Charmed]]''\n|Dark Priest\n|Episode: \"We're Off to See the Wizard\" (S 4:Ep 19)\n|\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Dead Like Me]]''\n| Gideon Jeffries\n| Episode: \"In Escrow\" (S 2:Ep 6)\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0556081/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm |title=Dead Like Me, In Escrow|website=IMDb.com |accessdate=30 August 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[JAG (TV series)|JAG]]''\n| Howie Black\n| Episode: \"Trojan Horse\" (S 9:Ep 22)\n| <ref name=\"TV,com\" />\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Alias (TV series)|Alias]]''\n| Miles Devereaux\n| Episode: \"The Index\" (S 4:Ep 10)\n| <ref name=\"TV\"/>\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Bones (TV series)|Bones]]''\n| Simon Graham\n| Episode: \"The Rocker in the Rinse Cycle\" (S 5:E 19)\n| \n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[The Finder (American TV series)|The Finder]]''\n| Icepick\n| Episode: \"Voodoo Undo\" (S 5:E 19)\n| \n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[NCIS (TV series)|NCIS]]''\n| Del Finney\n| Episode: \"[[NCIS (season 10)#Phoenix|Phoenix]]\" (S 10:Ep 3)\n| <ref name=\"TV\"/>\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation]]''\n| Marty 'The Cat' Kirch\n| Episode: \"Long Road Home\" (S 14:Ep 17)\n| <ref name=\"TV\"/>\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[MacGyver (2016 TV series)]]''\n| Nicholas Helman\n| Episode: \"Murdoc + Handcuffs\" (S 2:Ep 15)\n| <ref name=\"TV\"/>\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Film|Television|Music}}\n* [http://www.michaeldesbarres.com Official website]\n* {{IMDb name|id=0220735|name=Michael Des Barres}}\n* {{TV Guide|166011}}\n* [http://www.tv.com/people/michael-des-barres/ Michael Des Barres] at  [http://www.tv.com/people TV.com]\n\n{{The Power Station}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Des Barres, Michael}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:English male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male singers]]\n[[Category:English rock singers]]\n[[Category:Blues rock musicians]]\n[[Category:The Power Station (band) members]]\n[[Category:English people of French descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English actor and rock singer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP IMDb refimprove|date=January 2009}}\n{{COI|date=October 2019}}}} \n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name =\n| image = Michael Des Barres at the Chiller Theatre Expo 2017.jpg\n| caption = Des Barres at the Chiller Theatre Expo in 2017\n| background = solo_singer\n| alias =\n| birth_name = Michael Phillips Des Barres\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1948|1|24|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Hove]], [[Sussex]], England\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| origin = [[London]], England\n| occupation = Musician\n| genre = [[Rock music|Rock]]\n| spouse =\n| instrument = Vocals\n| years_active = 1960\u2013present\n| associated_acts = [[Silverhead]], [[Detective (band)|Detective]], [[Chequered Past]], [[The Power Station (band)|The Power Station]]\n| website =\n}}\n\n'''Michael Philip Des Barres''' (born 24 January 1948), the 26th Marquis Des Barres,<ref name=desbarreshome>{{cite web|title=About Michael Des Barres|url=http://michaeldesbarres.com/about/|website=Michaeldesbarres.com|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=100percentrock>{{cite web|title=In Conversation With: Michael Des Barres|url=http://magazine.100percentrock.com/interviews/201503/108997|website=100percentrock.com|date=27 March 2015}}</ref> is an English actor and rock singer. He is known for playing the [[recurring character|recurring role]] of [[Murdoc]] on the television show ''[[MacGyver (1985 TV series)|MacGyver]]'' and for replacing [[Robert Palmer (singer)|Robert Palmer]] in the band [[Power Station (band)|Power Station]], fronting the band at the 1985 [[Live Aid]] concert.<ref name=guitarhoo>{{cite web|title=Michael Des Barres Interview|url=http://www.guitarhoo.com/interviews/michael-des-barres-193|website=Guitarhoo.com|date=8 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nThe only child of Marquis Philip and Marquise Irene Des Barres, Michael Philip Des Barres was born and brought up in [[Hove]], [[Sussex]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/results/world-records/england-and-wales-births-1837-2006?firstname=michael&lastname=barres |title=Archived copy |access-date=17 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170807071721/http://search.findmypast.co.uk/results/world-records/england-and-wales-births-1837-2006?firstname=michael&lastname=barres |archive-date=7 August 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He attended [[Repton School]], a boarding school in [[Derbyshire]], and went on to attend the [[Corona Theatre School|Corona Academy]] drama school in London and appeared in several plays.<ref name=\"guitarhoo\"/>\n\n==Career==\n===Music===\nDes Barres formed his first teenage band, the Orange Illusion, with [[Nicholas Young (actor)|Nicholas Young]], [[Darryl Read]], and [[Kit Williams]], whilst they were all attending [[Corona Academy Stage School]] studying to be actors. The lineup, despite being broken up by the school's agent Hazel Malone, all went on to do greater things individually. Des Barres then formed [[Silverhead]] in England in 1972.<ref name=\"guitarhoo\"/>\n\nHe was part of the band [[Chequered Past]] from 1982 to 1985, which included [[Steve Jones (musician)|Steve Jones]] from [The] [[Sex Pistols]], [[Clem Burke]] and [[Nigel Harrison]] from [[Blondie (band)|Blondie]], and [[Tony Sales]] of [[Todd Rundgren]] ([[Runt (album)|Runt]]) and [[Tin Machine]] fame.<ref name=\"guitarhoo\"/>\n\nDes Barres met the members of [[Duran Duran]] when Chequered Past opened for a few shows during their 1984 tour. In 1985, when [[Robert Palmer (singer)|Robert Palmer]] withdrew from the Duran Duran side project [[Power Station (band)|Power Station]] just before their American summer tour, Des Barres was chosen to take his place as lead vocalist.<ref name=\"guitarhoo\"/>  \n\nOn 5 November 2013, The Michael Des Barres Band released a live album, ''Hot n Sticky Live'', which was recorded at the [[The Viper Room|Viper Room]] in Los Angeles in November 2012. The album is available as high quality mp3 downloads.<ref name=\"guitarhoo\"/>\n\nOn 7 April 2015 Des Barres released a solo album, ''The Key to the Universe''. Produced by Bob Rose at The Forum Music Village in Rome, the album reunites Des Barres with [[Nigel Harrison]] (former bassist of [[Blondie (band)|Blondie]] and [[Silverhead]]) on bass and guitar, in addition to Clive Deamer ([[Portishead (band)|Portishead]], [[Robert Plant]]) on drums, and Dani Robinson on guitar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/first-listen-michael-des-barress-album-the-key-115040755661.html|title=First Listen: Michael Des Barres\u2019s Album \u2018The Key to the Universe\u2019|website=Yahoo.com|accessdate=14 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, he formed The Mistakes, consisting of all veteran musicians \u2013 Loren Molinare (founding member of Little Caesar & The Dogs) on guitar, Eric Himel (Powerman 5000, host of The Sunset Jam) on guitar, Paul Ill (LA based musician with sales of over 20 million records as a studio musician and 4.5 million records as a songwriter) on bass guitar, and Matt Starr (studio and touring drummer with Guns N' Roses, Ace Frehley, Bonjovi & Whitesnake) on drums.  The band is signed to Steven Van Zant's Wicked Cool Records and has released 4 songs \u2013 Living in the USA/Gotta Serve Somebody (1/19/18) and Crackle and Hiss/Stop in the Name of Love (7/5/19).  The Mistakes will tour Japan in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://californiarocker.com/2019/08/25/interview-michael-des-barres-redefines-renaissance-man-performs-with-new-band-in-dtla-wednesday-night/|title=Interview: Michael Des Barres Redefines \"Renaissance Man\", Performs with New Band in DTLA Wednesday Night.|date=25 September 2019|website=Californiarocker.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=14 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Acting===\nDes Barres has appeared in over 100 different TV shows and almost 30 movies in his career. He first started acting at 8 years old as 'The Nux Bar Kid' on posters all over England. He appeared (uncredited) in the 1966 film starring Tony Curtis, ''Drop Dead Darling''. His first credited film role was as a supporting cast member in the classic 1967 film ''[[To Sir, with Love]]'', playing an East End pupil who always wears dark sunglasses indoors and out,<ref name=\"guitarhoo\"/> followed by a few other minor roles before he decided to pursue a career in music instead. He later concentrated his energies on acting again and was cast in ''[[Ghoulies]]'' (1985) as cult leader Malcolm Graves,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dreadcentral.com/news/91989/scream-factory-unleashes-ghoulies-ghoulies-2-blu-ray-details/|title=The Scream Factory Unleashes Ghoulies / Ghoulies 2 Blu-ray Details|date=4 March 2015|website=Dreadcentral.com|accessdate=November 14, 2019}}</ref> and ''[[Nightflyers (film)|Nightflyers]]'' (1987) as a charismatic empath. He worked opposite [[Clint Eastwood]] in 1989's ''[[Pink Cadillac (film)|Pink Cadillac]]''. His other film roles have included ''Midnight Cabaret'' (1990), ''[[Under Siege (film)|Under Siege]]'' (1992), ''[[Waxwork II: Lost in Time]]'' (1992), ''[[A Simple Twist of Fate]]'' (1994), and ''[[Sugar Town (film)|Sugar Town]]'' (1999). He also appeared in the 2004 film ''[[Catch That Kid]]'' and had a brief part in David Lynch's classic 2001 film ''[[Mulholland Drive]]''.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0166924/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast |title = Mulholland Drive (2001)|website=IMDb.com|accessdate=November 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn television, besides the role of Murdoc in ''[[MacGyver (1985 TV series)|MacGyver]]'', Des Barres was also a lead cast member of ''[[The New WKRP in Cincinnati]]'' during the 1991\u201392 season, as part of a husband-and-wife morning team. He had previously appeared on the original ''[[WKRP in Cincinnati]]'' as the lead singer of a punk band, Scum of the Earth. During this same time, he played a gay man ([[List of Roseanne characters#Leon Karp|Leon's]] boyfriend) in two episodes of ''[[Roseanne (TV series)|Roseanne]]''. He also played one of [[List of Roseanne characters#Darlene Conner Healy|Darlene's]] baby's doctors on one of the final episodes of the series. Some of his dozens of television appearances include ''[[Seinfeld]]'', ''[[Renegade (TV series)|Renegade]]'',  ''[[ALF (TV series)|ALF]]'', ''[[Ellen (TV series)|Ellen]]'', ''[[Nip/Tuck]]'', ''[[Just Shoot Me!]]'', ''[[Hart To Hart]]'', ''[[My Sister Sam]]'', ''[[Lois & Clark]]'' (which reunited him with another ''[[MacGyver (1985 TV series)|MacGyver]]'' recurring-character alumna, [[Teri Hatcher]] \u2013 the two had even appeared together in two ''[[MacGyver (1985 TV series)|MacGyver]]'' episodes), ''[[JAG (TV series)|JAG]]'', ''[[Melrose Place]]'', ''[[Nash Bridges]]'', ''[[Northern Exposure]]'', ''[[Rockford Files]]'', ''[[Sledge Hammer!]]'', ''[[Sliders]]'', ''[[St. Elsewhere]]'', ''[[21 Jump Street]]'',<ref name=\"guitarhoo\"/> ''[[The Pretender (TV series)|The Pretender]]'', ''[[Dead Like Me]]'', ''[[Frasier]]'', ''[[Hawaii (TV series)|Hawaii]]'', ''[[Bones (TV series)|Bones]]'', and ''[[NCIS (TV series)|NCIS]]'' (in the Season 10 episode \"[[Phoenix (NCIS)|Phoenix]]\").\n\nOn 23 October 2013, Des Barres joined the Los Angeles Philharmonic for the world premiere of ''200 Motels: The Suites'', by [[Frank Zappa]], in which he appeared as Rance, the narrator.<ref name=\"guitarhoo\"/>\n\n===Radio===\nCurrently, Des Barres hosts \"The Michael Des Barres Program\" every weekday morning from 8\u201311 AM ET with a replay every weekday evening from 9- midnight PT on Little Steven's [[Underground Garage]] ([[SiriusXM]] Channel 21). Over six million listeners hear an eclectic mix of rock, soul and punk, infused with Des Barres' extensive musical knowledge and his messages of positivity and longevity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://californiarocker.com/2019/08/25/interview-michael-des-barres-redefines-renaissance-man-performs-with-new-band-in-dtla-wednesday-night/|title=Interview: Michael Des Barres Redefines \"Renaissance Man\", Performs With New Band in DTLA Wednesday Night|website=Californiarocker.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=14 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMichael was married to Pamela Des Barres from 1977 until 1991.  They have a son, Nicholas Des Barres, a successful writer and video game designer. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.myheritage.com/research/record-10182-821620/nicholas-dean-des-barres-in-biographical-summaries-of-notable-people|title=Nicholas Dean Des Barres - Biographical Summaries of Notable People|website=Myheritage.com|accessdate=14 November 2019}}</ref>Des Barres has been sober since June 1981.<ref name=\"Google News archive\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2519&dat=19861005&id=g3RiAAAAIBAJ&sjid=E3cNAAAAIBAJ&pg=1574,809571|title=Observer-Reporter - Google News Archive Search|website=News.google.com|accessdate=14 November 2019}}</ref> In the mid-1980s he was one of the founding members of Rock Against Drugs.<ref name=\"New York Times\">{{cite news\n| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/03/10/business/advertising-rock-stars-deliver-anti-drug-messages.html| title=Rock stars deliver anti-drug messages|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]| accessdate=18 October 2012| date=10 March 1987| last1=Dougherty| first1=Philip H.}}</ref> He later did volunteer addiction counseling and worked with homeless teens. Des Barres has also organised and hosted the annual Don't Knock the Rock Film Festival, which first took place in 2003.<ref name=\"cinefamily.org\">{{cite web| url=http://www.cinefamily.org/films/dont-knock-the-rock-2012/| title=Don't Knock The Rock 2012| website=Cinefamily.org| accessdate=18 October 2012| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120826093428/http://www.cinefamily.org/films/dont-knock-the-rock-2012/| archive-date=26 August 2012| url-status=dead}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.myheritage.com/research/record-10182-821620/nicholas-dean-des-barres-in-biographical-summaries-of-notable-people|title=Nicholas Dean Des Barres - Biographical Summaries of Notable People|website=Myheritage.com|accessdate=14 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nDes Barres married his long-term partner, Britta Hayertz on December 21, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://californiarocker.com/2019/08/25/interview-michael-des-barres-redefines-renaissance-man-performs-with-new-band-in-dtla-wednesday-night/|title=Interview: Michael Des Barres Redefines \"Renaissance Man\", Performs with New Band in DTLA Wednesday Night.|date=25 August 2019|website=Californiarocker.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=14 November 2019}}</ref> Hayertz is the owner of Britta Morgan Pilates and also earned a [[Bachelor of Science|BSc]] in Plant Science from California State Polytechnic University, with special emphasis on urban forestry, water use issues, urban farming and sustainability.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://voyagela.com/interview/meet-britta-hayertz-pilates-britta-hancock-parklarchmont-blvd/|title=Meet Britta Hayertz of Pilates With Britta in Hancock Park and Larchmont Blvd.|date=20 March 2017|website=Voyagela.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=14 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Solo albums===\n* ''I'm Only Human'' (1980)\n* ''Somebody Up There Likes Me'' (1986)\n* ''The Key to the Universe'' (2015)\n\n===With Silverhead===\n* ''Silverhead'' (1972)\n* ''16 and Savaged'' (1973)\n* ''Live at the Rainbow'' (1975)\n\n===With Detective===\n* ''Detective'' (1977)\n* ''It Takes One to Know One'' (1977)\n* ''Live from the Atlantic Studios'' (1978)\n\n===With Chequered Past===\n* ''Chequered Past'' (1984)\n\n===With The Michael Des Barres Band===\n* ''Carnaby Street'' (2012)\n* ''Hot n Sticky Live'' (2013)\n\n== Filmography ==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n! ref\n|-\n| 1967\n| ''[[To Sir, with Love]]''\n| Williams\n|\n|-\n| 1971\n| ''[[I, Monster]]''\n| Boy in Alley\n| Released in the U.S. in 1973\n|<ref name=\"TV\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/people/michael-des-barres/|title=Michael Des Barres : Credit Listings |website=TV.com|accessdate=11 August 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[Ghoulies#Ghoulies (1985)|Ghoulies]]''\n| Malcolm Graves\n| American horror-comedy film\n| <ref name=\"TV\"/>\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[Pink Cadillac (film)|Pink Cadillac]]''\n| Alex\n| American action-comedy film\n| <ref name=\"TV\"/>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1992\n| ''[[Waxwork II: Lost in Time]]''\n| George\n| Horror-comedy film directed and written by [[Anthony Hickox]] and a sequel to the 1988 film ''[[Waxwork (1988 film)|Waxwork]]''.\n| <ref name=\"TV\"/>\n|-\n| ''[[Under Siege]]''\n| Domiani\n| Action thriller film directed by [[Andrew Davis (director)|Andrew Davis]]\n|\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[Poison Ivy: The New Seduction]]''\n| Ivan Greer\n| [[Erotic thriller]], drama and sequel to ''[[Poison Ivy (1992 film)|Poison Ivy]]'' (1992) and ''[[Poison Ivy II: Lily]]'' (1995).\n| <ref name=\"TV\"/>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1999\n| ''[[The Hungry Bachelors Club]]''\n| Mr. Spinner\n| Directed by Gregory Ruzzin, based on the novel of the same name by Lynn Scott Myers. The film was retitled ''Food for the Heart'' for its DVD release.\n| <ref name=\"TV\"/>\n|-\n| ''[[Sugar Town (film)|Sugar Town]]''\n| Nick\n| Independent film written and directed by [[Allison Anders]] and [[Kurt Voss]] about a web of chara