yver (2016 TV series)]]''\n| Nicholas Helman\n| Episode: \"Murdoc + Handcuffs\" (S 2:Ep 15)\n| <ref name=\"TV\"/>\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Film|Television|Music}}\n* [http://www.michaeldesbarres.com Official website]\n* {{IMDb name|id=0220735|name=Michael Des Barres}}\n* {{TV Guide|166011}}\n* [http://www.tv.com/people/michael-des-barres/ Michael Des Barres] at  [http://www.tv.com/people TV.com]\n\n{{The Power Station}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Des Barres, Michael}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:English male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male singers]]\n[[Category:English rock singers]]\n[[Category:Blues rock musicians]]\n[[Category:The Power Station (band) members]]\n[[Category:English people of French descent]]\n", "name_user": "Bug918", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Des_Barres"}
{"title_page": "World Federation of Workers in Food, Drink, Tobacco and Hotel Industries", "text_new": "The '''World Federation of Workers in Food, Drink, Tobacco and Hotel Industries''' ({{lang-fr|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration mondiale de travailleurs des industries alimentaires, du tabac et h\u00f4teli\u00e8re}}, FMATH) was a [[global union federation]] bringing together unions representing workers in food and service industries.\n\nThe federation was established on 10 October 1948 at a meeting in [[Marche-en-Famenne]].  Initially named the '''International Christian Federation of Food, Drink, Tobacco and Hotel Workers''', the federation was a merger of the International Federation of Christian Trade Unions of Workers in the Food and Drink Trades, the International Federation of Christian Tobacco Workers, and a federation of Christian hotel workers.  Like its predecessors, it affiliated to the [[International Federation of Christian Trade Unions]].<ref>{{cite web |title=World Federation of Workers in Food, Tobacco and Hotel Industries - WCL (WFFTH-WCL) |url=https://uia.org/s/or/en/1100016621 |website=UIA Open Yearbook |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy 1979, the federation's affiliates claimed a total of 250,000 members.<ref name=\"coldrick\">{{cite book |last1=Coldrick |first1=Percy |last2=Jones |first2=Philip |title=The International Directory of the Trade Union Movement |date=1979 |publisher=Facts on File |location=New York |isbn=0871963744 |pages=128&ndash;154}}</ref>  In 1982, it merged with the [[World Federation of Agricultural Workers]], to form the [[World Federation of Agriculture and Food Workers]].\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Food processing trade unions]]\n[[Category:Global union federations]]\n[[Category:World Confederation of Labour]]\n[[Category:Trade unions established in 1948]]\n[[Category:Trade unions disestablished in 1982]]\n", "text_old": "The '''World Federation of Workers in Food, Drink, Tobacco and Hotel Industries''' ({{lang-fr|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration mondiale de travailleurs des industries alimentaires, du tabac et h\u00f4teli\u00e8re}}, FMATH) was a [[global union federation]] bringing together unions representing workers in food and service industries.\n\nThe federation was established on 10 October 1948 at a meeting in [[Marche-en-Famenne]].  Initially named the '''International Christian Federation of Food, Drink, Tobacco and Hotel Workers''', the federation was a merger of the International Federation of Christian Trade Unions of Workers in the Food and Drink Trades, the International Federation of Christian Tobacco Workers, and a federation of Christian hotel workers.  Like its predecessors, it affiliated to the [[International Federation of Christian Trade Unions]].<ref>{{cite web |title=World Federation of Workers in Food, Tobacco and Hotel Industries - WCL (WFFTH-WCL) |url=https://uia.org/s/or/en/1100016621 |website=UIA Open Yearbook |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy 1979, the federation's affiliates claimed a total of 250,000 members.<ref name=\"coldrick\">{{cite book |last1=Coldrick |first1=Percy |last2=Jones |first2=Philip |title=The International Directory of the Trade Union Movement |date=1979 |publisher=Facts on File |location=New York |isbn=0871963744 |pages=128&ndash;154}}</ref>  In 1982, it merged with the World Federation of Agricultural Workers, to form the [[World Federation of Agriculture and Food Workers]].\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Food processing trade unions]]\n[[Category:Global union federations]]\n[[Category:World Confederation of Labour]]\n[[Category:Trade unions established in 1948]]\n[[Category:Trade unions disestablished in 1982]]\n", "name_user": "Warofdreams", "label": "safe", "comment": "link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Federation_of_Workers_in_Food,_Drink,_Tobacco_and_Hotel_Industries"}
{"title_page": "Elsa Respighi", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n[[Image:Respighis.jpg|thumb|right|240px|Elsa and Ottorino Respighi in the 1920s]]\n'''Elsa Respighi''' (n\u00e9e '''Olivieri-Sangiacomo''') (24 March 1894 \u2013 17 March 1996) was an Italian  singer and composer.  She was the wife and former pupil of [[Ottorino Respighi]].\n\n==Biography ==\nA singer ([[mezzo-soprano]]) and composer herself, Elsa Respighi created ballets out of Respighi's ''[[Ancient Airs and Dances]]'' suites and completed his final opera ''Lucrezia'' in 1937. Throughout her long life she championed her husband's work unfailingly. In 1955 she produced a memoir of her encounters with some of the most influential cultural figures of the early twentieth century. She also published a biography of Respighi in 1962.\n\nIn 1969 she established Fondo Respighi at the [[Fondazione Giorgio Cini]] in [[Venice]], to promote music education in Italy. She was also at the forefront of the 1979 Respighi Centenary celebrations, which saw a number of long-neglected works performed and recorded for the first time.<ref>http://www.musicweb-international.com/respighi/Adriano_Elsa_Vol6.htm</ref> Since then, several of her own works, chiefly for solo voice with accompaniment, have been given their premiere.\n\n==Works== \n<ref>https://www.allmusic.com/artist/elsa-respighi-mn0002344027</ref>\n\n''3 Canzoni su testi spagnoli''\n\n''4 Liriche dai Rubaiyat''\n\n''Berceuse bretonne''\n\n''Cantare Campagnolo''\n\n''Je n'ai rien''\n\n''La Mamma Povera''\n\n''Momento''\n\n''Duermete mi alma''\n\n''La muerte del Payador''\n\n''Due canzone Italiane''\n\n==Death ==\nShe died one week short of her 102nd birthday in 1996.\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Respighi, Elsa}}\n[[Category:1894 births]]\n[[Category:1996 deaths]]\n[[Category:Female composers]]\n[[Category:Italian centenarians]]\n[[Category:Italian mezzo-sopranos]]\n[[Category:20th-century Italian composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Italian singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century women singers]]\n[[Category:Women centenarians]]\n\n\n{{Italy-composer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n[[Image:Respighis.jpg|thumb|right|240px|Elsa and Ottorino Respighi in the 1920s]]\n'''Elsa Respighi''' (n\u00e9e '''Olivieri-Sangiacomo''') (24 March 1894 \u2013 17 March 1996) was an Italian  singer and composer.  She was the wife and former pupil of [[Ottorino Respighi]].\n\n==Biography ==\nA singer ([[mezzo-soprano]]) and composer herself, Elsa Respighi created ballets out of Respighi's ''[[Ancient Airs and Dances]]'' suites and completed his final opera ''Lucrezia'' in 1937. Throughout her long life she championed her husband's work unfailingly. In 1955 she produced a memoir of her encounters with some of the most influential cultural figures of the early twentieth century. She also published a biography of Respighi in 1962.\n\nIn 1969 she established Fondo Respighi at the [[Fondazione Giorgio Cini]] in [[Venice]], to promote music education in Italy. She was also at the forefront of the 1979 Respighi Centenary celebrations, which saw a number of long-neglected works performed and recorded for the first time.<ref>http://www.musicweb-international.com/respighi/Adriano_Elsa_Vol6.htm</ref> Since then, several of her own works, chiefly for solo voice with accompaniment, have been given their premiere.\n\n==Works== \n<ref>https://www.allmusic.com/artist/elsa-respighi-mn0002344027</ref>\n\n''3 Canzoni su testi spagnoli\n\n''4 Liriche dai Rubaiyat\n\n''Berceuse bretonne\n\n''Cantare Campagnolo\n\n''Je n'ai rien\n\n''La Mamma Povera\n\n''Momento\n\n''Duermete mi alma\n\n''La muerte del Payador\n\n''Due canzone Italiane\n\n==Death ==\nShe died one week short of her 102nd birthday in 1996.\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Respighi, Elsa}}\n[[Category:1894 births]]\n[[Category:1996 deaths]]\n[[Category:Female composers]]\n[[Category:Italian centenarians]]\n[[Category:Italian mezzo-sopranos]]\n[[Category:20th-century Italian composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Italian singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century women singers]]\n[[Category:Women centenarians]]\n\n\n{{Italy-composer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jonesey95", "label": "safe", "comment": "FixLintererrors", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elsa_Respighi"}
